## 5. Update your Chef Automate user with an SSH public key

At this point, you have a user account and its initial password set up.

You need to associate your public SSH key with your Chef Automate user. This key enables you to authenticate requests to Chef Automate from the command line.

In practice, you would [generate an SSH keypair](https://www.digitalocean.com/community/tutorials/how-to-set-up-ssh-keys--2). The Windows workstation comes with an SSH keypair that you can use in the <% fp 'C:\Users\Administrator\\\.ssh' %> directory. <% fp 'id_rsa' %> is the private part of the keypair; <% fp 'id_rsa.pub' %> is the public part.

Copy the public part of your SSH key, <% fp 'C:\Users\Administrator\\\.ssh\id_rsa.pub' %>, to the clipboard. You can open the file in a text editor or run this from your PowerShell prompt.

```ps
# C:\Users\Administrator
$ Get-Content C:\Users\Administrator\.ssh\id_rsa.pub | clip
```

Next, log in to the Chef Automate web interface from Google Chrome. [https://delivery.chordata.biz/e/mammalia/#/login](https://delivery.chordata.biz/e/mammalia/#/login)

Enter your username and password for the user you set up in [step 3](#step3).

Next, select **Organizations** from the drop-down menu in the upper right corner.

![](automate/wf-select-admin.png)

From the **Users** tab, select your username and then paste your SSH key into the text area under **Security Information**.

![](automate/wf-add-ssh-key.png)

Click **Save & Close**.

[END_BOX]

